S But what do we say to the principle of law which I too have laid down elsewhere, that anybody and everybody is bound to hand over to the victor the property and the person of the vanquished? It is quite evident under this principle that the territory of another ought not to be a place of succor to the vanquished. But in the same passage my reply has been that this doctrine may be affirmed in the case of a complete victory, not in the case of a small success. And here it does not follow that, if it is lawful for a victor to try to secure the spoils, it may also be lawful per se for him to take them, or even that he who

rules a territory may always be required to turn them over to the victor.
